ding high levels of mobilization to effect dramatic change, played a central role in the region and that divergent development outcomes can be attributed to the interplay between campaigns and institutions. The analysis departs from common portrayals of the developmental state as wholly technocratic and demonstrates that rural development was not just a byproduct of industrialization. Looney's research is based on several years of fieldwork in Asia and makes a unique contribution by systematically comparing China's development experience with other countries. Relevant to political science, economic history, rural sociology, and Asian Studies, the book enriches our understanding of state-led development and agrarian change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aRural developmentxGovernment policyzChina. 0aRural developmentxGovernment policyzKorea (South). 0aRural developmentxGovernment policyzTaiwan. 0aRural developmentzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aRural developmentzEast Asia. 0aRural developmentzKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aRural developmentzTaiwanxHistoryy20th century. 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Economic Development.2bisacsh  adevelopmental state, rural development, East Asia, mobilization campaigns, economy of development.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2020 Englishz978311070479208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is par